Francisco Muiva Jou, San Lorenzo de Moxos, 05/05/2008,
Before, I was strong enough to serve the authority (the indigenous government).
tapuemmaapo nichnrao eto ... nkownorakrepo nae no juesiono
Pas rcemment car poque sans boeufs.
Recin yo tuve fuerza para servir a los autoridades.
There was one who took care of us, the authority, the cacique, the 'capitn' and the 'comisario'.
emjaai ma tjaokowrii ma juesi , kasike o kapitn , o komisario .
Habia que nos cuidaba, el autoridad, el cacique, el capitan y el comisario.
They were taking care of us so that we went to work, so that we didnt fall down during our work, we didnt walk with the load, (because) we were tired and our shoulder hurts.
eno tkunewokovionrii puejchu vyana te to motneko , puejchu te to vkuvnopo wo vkimyonrichjicha viti yvitaripo tkotiripo to vjiu .
\to eno tkunewokovionrii puejchu te to motneko, puejchu ikuvnopo wo ikimyonrichicha viti yvitaripo tkotiripo to ijiu.
\fo Ellos nos cuidaban para que no nos caigamos en el trabajo, que no sigamos con la carga, ya nos cansamos nuestros hombros.
Ellos nos cuidaban para que vayamos al trabajo, para que no nos caigamos en el trabajo, que no sigamos con la carga, ya nos cansamos nuestros hombros.
And then, we left it one or two hours, and right after the authorities put it on our shoulders, they put it on us.
ene takepo veraikwopo vkeripo una hora o dos hora , tapuemmawo tnokjichoviono eno kparaakono , enopo tnokovi .
Y despus lo dejamos una hora o dos horas, y recin los pona en nuestros hombros los autoridades.
They didn't put it on us because it was heavy.
wo vitjivina ( vi @) jicho wo waato tyjitakore eto [ interrupcion ]
No les pona a nosotros porque era pesado.
That's it. (Before) they put it on our shoulders and we carried it there, and we piled it.
takeei ; vkonokjipo ene vkitekpopo te pjoro uko ... vkoomutkopo
takeei; vkonokjiu pjoro ene ukitekpopo te pjoro uko... ukoomutkopo
As es. Nos los ponian nuestros hombros y as lo haciamos llegar all, y los amontaneabamos.
There was a lot of people, children and adults, women and men.
chopemuri , moverano chaniono moperono , seno jiro , seno jiro
Habia harta gente, chicos y mayores, mujeres y hombres.
The women used to go with us, they carried it on their head.
vkochane no seno veno senono nakoyposi
Nos acompaaban las mujeres, le ponian en su cabeza.
There weren't oxen yet (in the village), but people living in the countryside (coming from far away) had oxen and cart.
tajinachoo tkoviyerano chaono pero enericho te to ewire nakoyeye to wiye ( to ) kareta .
No habia todavia bueyes (en el pueblo), pero tenia bueyes y carreton la gente del campo (de lejos).
asike te pjoka wicho tajinachoo eto .
SY0: te pjoka tajinach'o (suffit), pas de wich'o
as que aqu no habia todavia.
That's why we always carried it on our shoulder (lit. It was always on our shoulder), in our hands, we carried anything, we carried everything needed to (build) the church.
takeei takericho muiriji te to vijiu te to ywupe viomo to tajpuka viomo to taechgiene pjoka resia .
muiriji te to ijiu, te to iwupe [...] resia.
Por eso que era siempre en nuestro hombro, en nuestras manos lo llevamos cualquier cosa, lo llevamos lo que se pensaba para (construir) la iglesia.
Before we were working at the church (for the construction of the church), it is the church site that was getting filled (with dirt).
kopeni etoricho muetneko pjoka resia , etogiene pjoka resia eto muetneko tkomuupa .
Antes era el trabajo la iglesia, es la iglesia que se terraplenaba.
Also, each 'parcialidad' (ritual groups) gathered its own group (the members) its the same as being a servant
tomuire to ... cada parcielidad , cada parcielidad takoomutko eno taewnochanrii kutiripo nae no mosono ... (...)
pas de to devant cada parcielidad... taewunochanrii
end of sentence is not audible
Tambien cada parcialidad lo juntaba su grupo (los miembros), es igual ser de mozo
It's like people who have a servant (rich people), it was the same for us
tkomosorano chane ene takeei te vyee viti .
como la gente rica as era para nosotros
como la gente que tiene mozo as era para nosotros
And we gathered to go to the village and to work there, they made us work, we were sent, we have been sent as authorities.
ene ymutu to vkemtoneyore vyopyore vkemtone tajichrii , ywnoi vkownopo mue ma tparaako .
viumutu, ukemtone, najichrii, iwonoi, ukounopo muema kparaako
Y nos reunimos para ir al pueblo y trabajar, nos hacian trabajar, nos mandaba y nos mandaba hacer el autoridad.
The authority called us, the great 'capitan' or the cacique, they called all of us.
tichorikoopo ma kparaako , kapitampuka o kasikipuka , ymutu
Nos llam el autoridad, capitan grande o ser cacique, toditos nosotros.
And we are going to dream, we are going to work, maybe during one month we were doing it.
ene ywopuchyore vkemtoneyore , vittorojpo etonapka koje vjicho .
Y vamos a soar vamos a trabajar durante sera un mes tuvimos haciendo.
vittorojpo ypuemmaapo vyono vchowo te to santi .
Terminamos y recien volvimos al chaco.
We finished it and right after we came back to our field. That's how it went. Two or three people went to bring something to eat from the field.
takoe eto ; tyonontsero eno apinano moponano tvejnono eto tnikkore te to santi .
As fue. Se fueron dos o tres a traer para comer del chaco.
They went to bring, it was still carried on the shoulder or with a shoulder pole.
Fueron a traer, era todavia a hombro o naracuraqui.
The shoulder pole was as big as this tree.
tkonorogi manjee ( jmani ykugi enegi @) joka jee pereano .
El naracuraqui era grueso como este pelea (palo).
They brought bananas, manioc or rice or corn.
Con eso trajeron platano, yuca, o arroz o maiz.
It was our suffering of our life.
chopemuuricho to vsufrichwo te to vitorisra , viti , chaniono trinranono
\to chopemuricho to usufrichwo ... ( rcouter quand mme si bien uu long)
'chopemuerich'o to usufrichwo confirm comme correct par Florencia
Era nuestro sufrimiento en nuestra vida
There weren't the 'carayanas' here yet, they were still far away, they were close to Trinidad.
no tkomeriono najinaricho te pjoka , ewirericho onogi tericho Trinrapai .
no habia todavia los carayanas aqu, eran lejos todavia, eran cerca de Trinidad.
Rich people who own cattle weren't living here yet, they weren't here yet.
enericho nowo eno rikono tkoyono to waka , te pjoka ( tajina.. .) najinarichooi
Todavia no vivian aqu los ricos que tienen ganado, na habia aqu.
After seeing (when they see) that it was a good village (populated one), a beautiful place, with a beautiful central square, a beautiful church,
takeptsero te to manjeepo naemopo wosarepo mrakarii pjoka tyuunapo pjoka ... manjee prasa tyuunapo pjoka resia .
Despus (cuando ?) vieron que era un pueblo fuerte (poblado), ya bonito aqu, bonita ya la plaza, bonita ya la iglesia;
they came here, and now they have grocery stores, the ones who have money
tyuterekompo asta juiti tkoyompo pulperia , tkoyenoviono to plata ,
se vinieron, hasta ahora ya tienen pulperia, los que tienen plata.
And now we buy things (in their stores).
Before we were not used to buy things, there was no need to buy.
Antes no compramos, no teniamos que comprar.
Everything there could be, we needed: machete, axe, shovel, blanket to make mosquito net, fabric to make pants, in the city of Trinidad.
muirijiricho to ... manjee ... etjopka vkomnu saype , ywoti , kaecha , colcha chakuyore muipuereyore te Trinra
Siempre necesitabamos machete si habia, hacha, pala, colcha para taparse (para mosquitero), corte (tela) para hacer pantalones, en Trinidad
We go there and we come back again with the cart, coming back (with a canoe) was still difficult.
ene vkige , vchowriojno , te kareta , te pkure , vchowo kuestaricho
ene ukige uchowriojno te kareta te pkure, uchowo kuestaricho
all nos vamos y volvemos otra vez en carretn, volver (en canoa) costaba todavia.
Our food was brought from here, (they took with them) the rice, the corn, the sugar, also onions, cheese and garlic,
ene , ene , pero etjo tnikkore ene te pjoka toso , to arusu , to sponi , to asuka , tyompo to sevoya , tyompo to giesu , tyompo eto josi ,
El que comer de aqu lo llevaban, el arroz, el maiz, el azucar, llevaban ceboya, llevaban queso, llevaban ajo,
El que comer vena de aqu, el arroz, el maiz, el azucar, tambin ceboya, queso, y ajo,
That's what we sold in the city of Trinidad.
etorii ( tajrori ...) tkijroriksi te to Trinra .
eso era lo que se vendia en Trinidad.
So to go far away was really difficult, one week traveling sitting in the back (of the cart), so this cold caught us anywhere.
asike ewire kuesta , etona semana to ypuisra , tkutgiene pjuena tkosarai tchimrokovi oypuka ene .
Asi que ir lejos costaba mucho, una semana de viaje atrasito (del carretn), as como esta fri nos pillaba en cualquier parte.
We couldn't keep traveling, we waited until the weather got better and we walked again.
wo waatoo to vimyanapojcha vkuchokyo to tetpirikwopo ene ypuikoriojno .
pour Leo: vimyanapojcha et non vimyanapojicha
No podemos seguir viajando, lo esperamos hasta que se componga el tiempo y caminabamos otra vez.
And it was the same in the canoe.
takeei te to pkure enerichu takoe
Y as tambien en la canoa es lo mismo.
We used to stay and sleep, stay and sleep.
Nos quedaban a dormir, nos quedaban a dormir;
Nos quedabamos a dormir, nos quedabamos a dormir.
When the weather was good, the travel in the cart lasted no more than two days.
to tyuunajcha to tiempo , to kareta apinarichu sache .
Cuando era buen tiempo, en carretn eran dos dias no ms.
And with the canoe, (it lasted) one day, from here, from San Lorenzo.
ene te to pkure , tona sache , te pjoka Sa Lorenzo .
Y en canoa, un da, de aqu, de San Lorenzo.

When the weather was good, when it was not raining, it (the weather) didn't make us late, we get up early here, when it is still half dark, maybe at six o'clock, because at seven o'clock the sun rises.
to tyuuna to sachono , tajina wo tgiwa , tajina temtokavi , vechpukowne te pjoka , tmopkukuiricho , te las seypuka , porke te las siete tyuchkopo to sache .
Cuando estaba bueno el tiempo, no habia lluvia, na habia que nos atrase, madrugamos aqu cuando todavia es medio oscuro, puede ser a las 6 porque a las 7 sale el sol
At six o'clock it was not dark anymore, the day became clearer, and we would leave (lit. we go)
te las sey tyurimuirisrapo tyjarakuyrepo to sache , vyompo
A las 6 ya veia, aclarando el dia, nos vamos.
We go with our travel food we cooked.
vyongienejicha ... to vniipooi manjee taetrewo tamagi .
Nos vamos nuestra tapeque, hecho cocido.
They cook it here, cake, rice bread after the jerky, the butter has onions inside, so that when we cook, we take off the butter and we put it in the pot.
naemagicho te pjoka , viskocho , pan de arroz , tyompo eto to chragi , to mateka tyono sevoya , pajchu te wkometsipo yvepo to ... yvepo to mateka vepchoko te to metsi tyuunai .
Lo cuecen aqu, bizcocho, pan de arroz despues el charque, la manteca tiene cebolla, para que cuando cocinamos, saquemos la manteca y la ponemos en la olha
And it's (butter + onions) going to be good to eat with the meat.
ya va a ser linda para comer con la carne
The meat is grinded, cooked and roasted.
to vaka tkoywa taeturewo tmagi asaw .
La carne es molida, cocida, y asada.
When we are traveling, we don't make an effort to grind a lot the food of our pot.
takeei wipo viaptawiirigia onogi vyuwajigiariini taecheejina to ymetsi
all en el viaje ya no estamos afanando a moler para su racha de nuestra olha..
They don't do it for the travel
te ... to ... wo ... manjee ... wo naekmunacha to viaje .
They cut it, it is how they do the travel food.
Lo pican, as lo hacen la comida viajero.
That's how it was when we came back here
Sometimes In the city of Trinidad, there were only Japanese people,
etjo ... enjo ... te to Trinra muirijiricho Japonesiono , to tkoyono eto Japonesi ...

They used to have their fabric, they had what we call axe, shovel, machete, adz, in order to work and plow like the planks, the adz arranges, the chisel to gouge the wood (lit. the stick), to do chairs, to do tables, that's it.

tkoyono eto attaji , tkoyono eto tkijare ywoti , kaecha , saype , asaera , wkemtoneyoyre vewchorisoyre to kutgiene mani tawra , eto asaera , eto tetpiriko , tatakuupa vettakrisoyre to wkugi , siyayorepuka , mesayore etorii .
attaji [...] iwoti [...] vettatkrisoyre, ukemtoneoyre (deberia ser kutiyore en lugar de kutgiene)

tenan su corte, tenan lo que se llama hacha, pala, machete, azuela, para trabajar y labrar para tabla como las tablas, la azuela acomoda, escoplo para escoplar el palo, para hacer sillas, para hacar mesas eso es.
That is bought, there in the city of Trinidad it is bought. There wasn't it here yet. When we were going to lend, it is difficult to lend (something) to a person.
etjo tkowachriksi , enerichu te to Trinra , muiriji , tajinachoo te jmani to wkopjikoko kuesta wkoprigia mue ma chane .
Eso se compra, all mismo siempre se compra en Trinidad. No habia aqu todavia. Cuando nos ibamos a prestar cuesta que le prestamos al hombre.
Some people didnt want to lend his iron, his chisel, drill bit and adz, that thing we call Villa Barquilla (tool to make holes).
emjaai chane wo muesopa to ... mayee giero , muettakropa , wroka , asaera , tyompo eto to tkijareei villa barquilla .
Villa Barquilla : outil pour faire des trous
Hay hombre que no le deja prestar su hierro, su escoplo, broca, y azuela, ese que se llama Villa Barquilla.
That thing drills until it perforates the other side.
Ese orada hasta que orada al otro lado.
Look this drill, this is the word for this (thing).
pia joka tkami , joka taejare joka .
Mira este orada, este es su nombre de este.
That has been drilled by a drill bit.
Ese es orada de la broca.
That thing is expensive if the owner wants us to pay for it (rent).
ene eto kuesta ma tkoye mawooo ywaoka .
eso cuesta donde el dueo quiere que se lo paguen.
Some men are not good, some are good, affectionate, they know about our suffering.
emjaai woi tyuuri , tyuuna chane temnai , muemoti to manjeeyore viatajiwono viti .
Sylvia: hay un hombre que no es bueno.
je comprends pas pourquoi pas d'IRR sur tyuuri
Hay hombres que no son buenos, hay hombres buenos, cariosos, que conocen el sufrimiento de nosotros.
Some men don't know about our suffering, they just get angry:
emjaai wo muemoti to viatajiwo , tsemchujcha :
hay hombres que no conocen el sufrimiento, se enoja no ms :
"Why don't you buy it, why don't you go to buy it", the man said to him.
" wo jwachrigiarii , wo pyanarii , wo jwachrigiarii ", majicho ema chane .
vraiment -ri'i la deuxime fois ? ou rako ?
Porque no compras, porque no vas a comprar", le dijo el hombre.
It was the same with my deceased father (during his life), we were poor, we had almost nothing, but when he went to travel, when he came back, we finally had clothes.
kutirii ma tataeni , powrewokovi , tajina wakyee tamtu pero te tyonrii , te to viaje ene te tchoopo , ypuemmaapo eto pjoka ymuiio ,
era como mi finado padre, eramos pobres, no tenemos todo, pero cuando se iba en viaje, cuando volvi, recin teniamos ropa.
There was only the material (fabric), a poor material.
takejworichu to naetsmeeji , naetsmeeji , joro naetsmeeji .
solo habia los tejidos, pobre tejidos.
And they were making blankets, in olden days, and hammocks like these ones, we call it hammocks.
ene eto ... tkepia ... tkepia eto colcha , ante , tyompo eto achuchicha kutgiene jena , tkijare achu
tkutgiene jmani [devrait tre takutgiene jena, -chicha indica el adulo, Florencia confirme que kutgiene jena]
Y se hacian colchas, antes era la hamaca como la de ahora, que se llaman hamaca.
Y se hacian colchas, antes, y las hamaquitas como aquellas, que se llaman hamaca.
We covered ourselves with it, and during the nights, we were cold, we get up and went close to the fire to get warmed.
eto wkepkou ene to yotyono wkosarecho vechpuko viosokowo te yuku .
eto ukepkou ento yotyono ukosarecho vechpuko viosokowo te yuku.
Eso nos tapamos, y en las noches, nos hacia frio, nos levantamos a calentar en el fuego.
We get warmed, and came back (in our hammocks).
Nos calentamos, nos entrabamos (en los hamacas).
Before we were suffering a lot.
And our mother, when we were children, heated her son's diaper close to the fire, we were still urinating (bedwetting), we were still children.
ene su veno te moyowokovi ( tyosoj ...) tyosojiriko to tattajra to schicha , yjoraricho moyowokowsiraricho .
Accent: tyosojriko ? "sira" = gira ou -ko-ira ? mais analyse de ko ?
Y nuestra madre, cuando somos chicos, calentaba su paal de su hijo en el fuego, somos orinoncitos, eramos chiquitos todavia.
Our mother suffered a lot, but our father, my mother's husband, he brought big firewood so that the fire didn't put out during the night, until it dawns again.
sufrichwo esu veno chope pero ema ma viya , viyarii saema esu veno , ( esu ...) ema tnerikrii , manriko to chpegie wkugi puejchu wo tema to yuku , tayuutiko yoti asta to sacheriwre .
D'aprs Lo, t- obligatoire devant sufrichwo, mais ne s'entend pas.
Nuestra madre sufri mucho, pero nuestro padre, el esposo de mi madre, l traiya lea gruesa para que no se apague el fuego toda la noche hasta que amanece otra vez.
I went to bring some firewood, good firewood called 'vergologo', 'blanquillo' firewood, alder wood, with firewood from 'jorori' tree, we call it 'paci' firewood.
nvejnooi to tojgieru , tyuuna tojgieru tkijare kjegie , ktsogi , rsagi tyompo manjee wchugi , vijarecho kopopgi ,
Me iba a traer lea, lea buena que se llama vergologo, lea blanquillo, palo alizo, con lea de palo jorori, le llamamos lea de paca,
These ones heat us, they are the ones who are good for the fire.
eto jmani tijrechovi eto tynako to yuku .
estos son los que (nos) calientan, que guardan el fuego.
the fire is there, it doesn't put out, with that fire she heats the diapers, our mother
sans "nuestra madre" (litt. ella que nos tuvieron de hijo)
ah esta el fuego, no se apaga, con eso calienta ella los paales, nuestra madre
This is what I have seen in my life when I grew up.
eto nimogne te to nitorisra te to njuukopo .
Eso lo v en mi vida, cuando crec.
We were suffering a lot because we were poor.
Our wealth has always been the fields, the rice, the corn, bananas, the manioc used to do the 'chiv' (manioc flour) sold in Trinidad.
to vyeerii rikesa eto muiriji eto to skureko , to arusu , to sponi , keeno , kujpa , jarinayore , tyono te Trinra
Nuestra riqueza era siempre las plantaciones, el arroz, el maiz, pltanos, la yuca para hacer chiv que iba a Trini.
The one who has cattle milks.
and the cheese was still expensive, it was expensive.
y era caro tadavia el queso, era caro.
It was expensive, there wasn't a lot of money yet, but the fabric was still cheap in the Casa Suarez of Japanese people.
siwacho wicho chopemurina plata pero to ... to attaji warattoricho tericho Ware , ( te ) nae no Japonesiono .
on n'entend pas de t avant swacho, comme avant sufrichwo en 70. wich'o 'chopemurina plata confirm comme correct par Florencia
Era caro todavia, es harta plata.
on n'entend pas de t avant swacho car absence de dents ? te'icho ?
Era caro, no habi harta plata todavia, pero el corte era todavia barato en la Casa Suarez, de los Japoneses.
And what is called 'meter' arrived, before we used the term 'barra' (measure unit).
eto titekpopo to tkijare metro , te to ante antiguogienejicha eto wara .
Y lleg lo que se llama 'metro', antes era la barra no mas.

The barra is equal to four cuartas. What is called 'old barra' arrived, because the meter is equal to five cuartas and the barra four cuartas, it is called 'old barra', old measure used to buy the fabric.
kwatru pewou to wararii , titekpo to manjee tkijareei to metro porke to metro sinko pewou , to wara kwatru pewou , tkijare to wara antiguo , chosgiene , tawachrisowyo ( te to ) to attaji .
Era quatro cuarta la barra. Lleg lo que se llama barra antiguo, porque el metro tiene cinco cuarta, y la barra quatro cuarta, se llama la barra antiguo, viejo para comprar el corte.
Fabric was still sold at retail, it was thick.
to attajrii muirijiricho te piesa , mittuoricho .
El corte era todavia a la pieza, era gruesa.
And there weren't yet fabrics of all the colors, imperial, sparse, what is called 'chamarote'.
ene tajinachoo posraarujina eto attaji , impriare , etomji , etopo to tkijareei chamarote .
chamarote semble tre avec accent ppal sur syll 1 et secondaire sur syll 3, peut-tre d l'effet d'"annonce"
Y no habia todavia de todos colores, imperial, ralito, lo que se llama chamarote.
The 'chamarote' is thick, it is good for making pants.
El chamarote es grueso, sirve para pantaln.
That's how it still was, the fabrics were without color.
takericho wicho takajujuji to ... to manjee to ... attajono .
As era todavia, no eran pintados los cortes.
Then Trinidad started to get rich.
takepo te to tpajkopripo manjee rikoporipo to Trinra .
De ah ya se fue enriqueciendo Trinidad.
Then what is called 'floral fabric' arrived, the silk fabric arrived, from two kind of silk : the thin silk is thick, the ordinary one is loosely woven.
tyutekpo eto tkijare eto to ... prremo attaji , tyutekpo eto sera attaji , to serarii apimri eto , to sera : sera vina eto tjtumo , to sera ordinario eto tveejmo .
Despus ya lleg lo que se llama corte floreado, lleg el corte de seda, de dos clases de seda la seda fina es gruesa, la seda ordinaria es ralita.
That's how it was then, depending on what the woman wanted for her 'tipoy' (traditional dress).
takerichooi segn to swooogne su seno , to smuiyore ,
Despus era as, segun lo que queria la mujer para su tipoy.
The lace was still expensive. And the ribbon, two meters of ribbon, for the festivity, mixed, and the woman and the ladies dance during the festivity.
eto karoricho to ronta , etopo to sinta , to sinta , apina metru sinta , tayeeyore te to piesta , te to srgiji siimuisoyre te to piestano su seno , veno seno .
La blonda era todavia cara. Despus la cinta, dos metros de cinta, para la fiesta, entreverado para bailar en las fiestas la mujer y las Seoras.
Then the other lace is put here, and the other one here. (up and down).
ene etopo to pona ronta ene te pjoka towriko
despus la otra blonda aqu se pone y la otra aqu. (arriba y abajo).
They are called 'awaresas' (old women), they called them 'sisters'between them in Trinidad and also here.
eno no tkijarionrii pnoni eemananrii pnoni , pnoni te Trinra ( nono ) eto naejare eemanano pnoni .
Se llaman las awaresas, ellas se llamaban en Trinidad hermanas y aqu tambien.
There were two 'awaresas' who had a cape,
awaresano apinano enopo tkoyono kapa , awaresano (??)
mais ono+ ina ne devraient pas faire aena
Habia dos awaresas que tenian capa,
The sisters who look like the nuns weren't all awaresas.
wo namtu awaresaena pnoni eemananrii nakutirii pnoni monjano pnoni monjano .
no eran todas awaresas las hermanas que parecen a las monjas.
In our language, we say 'nun', like the 'nuns'. We say like that, like once time we said to the sisters. We say like that.
